	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Study now available on the sustainability of agro-industry under an EPA</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 October 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p>The revised inception report released in August 2004 on the study on the sustainability impact assessment of EPAs that is being conducted jointly by the EU and the ACP has a major section dealing with agro-industry in west Africa. This reviews progress in the negotiations so far, with emphasis placed on ‘improving regional integration and the improvement of competitiveness of west African economies’. The central question to be addressed in the main report is how will ‘liberalisation of trade and investment under an EPA ... affect the development of a competitive agro-industry in western Africa’.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p>The report reviews the importance of the agricultural sector (which provides employment for 53% of the economically active population) and the scale of the challenge faced if competitiveness is to be achieved. ‘The export of food products from the EU into western Africa can have negative effects on local production, illustrated by the imports of wheat or meat products, which threaten local production of cereals, but respond to a certain demand of urban consumers’. The importance of developing value-adding activities around agricultural production for national, regional and international markets is emphasised, as is the importance of developing regional trade in food and agricultural products (where the absence of infrastructure such as ‘cold chains’ is seen as important). The inception report identifies four main areas to be reviewed in the main study: fresh fruit and vegetables, cotton, cereals and meat and meat products.</p><p>In the fruit-and-vegetable sector the emphasis is on exploring constraints on the development of exports to the EU. In the cotton sector the study will look at the scope for the development of a clothing industry. In the cereals sector the focus will be on the impact of imports from the EU on domestic production and consumption patterns. In the meat and meat-products sector the focus will be on the ‘risk of increased competition between local and imported products from the EU ... and the challenges facing development of processing’. The important question addressed in the study is ‘how potential negative impacts related to competition between EU products and local producers can be limited or avoided’. Particular attention will be paid to the impact of SPS requirements on export competitiveness.</p><p>Key themes to be explored in all case studies are:</p>
<ul>

<li>the impact on tax revenues; </li>

<li>the impact on GDP and external trade; </li>

<li>the impact on investment; </li>

<li>the impact on small and medium enterprises; </li>

<li>the impact on related sectors. </li>

</ul>
<p>In terms of social sustainability, key themes for the agriculture component of the study include: the impact on employment; wages and poverty; food security; and the gender impact. Two basic scenarios will be explored:</p>
<ul>

<li>continuation of current levels of liberalisation and existing trends;</li>

<li>completely free access for west African countries to the EU market and for the EU to west African markets for 70% and 80% of current exports.</li>

</ul>
<p>Both scenarios are to take into account the impact on regional integration based on the assumption of the creation of an ECOWAS free-trade area by the end of 2004 and a customs union by the end of 2007.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

